body:
Add utility code to support `in/not in` operators for STL containers.
Currently supports `std::vector`, `std::set` and `std::unordered_set`.

Thinking about it, it would make sense to extend this to `std::map` and `std::unordered_map` too.
Comments, and suggestions of other STL containers to support, welcome.

Closes #3652

comment_data.body:
I don't think this is worth a separate file. Just add it as a new section to the end of CppSupport.cpp.

Also, can you maybe split a part of it off into an implementation section (without the `.proto`)? That would make it appear later in the generated C++ file where it's less in sight for users. I think we only need the `is_in()` function to be available for the generated user code, and thus be declared in the `.proto` section, right?
We prefix all internal user visible names with `__pyx_` in order to avoid conflicts.

Let's keep this simple.
```suggestion
            return "(%s __operator_in_containers_helpers__::is_in(%s,%s))" % (
                "!" if self.operator == 'not_in' else "",
                operand1.result(),
                operand2.result())
```

comment_data.body:
I think we should read the exception configuration from the C++ methods, shouldn't we? And neither `begin()`, `end()`, `find()`, nor `contains()` are declared as raising exceptions at least in our libcpp STL declarations. However, we also have to deal with user implemented containers here, so I'd suggest looking up all four methods and trying to find the most appropriate exception setup from that, if at least one of them declares exceptions. I'd go for `contains()` first, then look up `find()`, then fall back to `end()`, then `begin()`, and take the first exception configuration that we find.

Note that, if we need to handle exceptions, then we also need to set `self.is_temp = True` to make sure that we pass the return value through a temporary variable inside of the try-block.
